e images of Oceania were filtered to a wider British public through the gradual emergence of a new idea of fame - commodified, commercial, scandalous - which bore in some respects a striking resemblance to modern celebrity culture and which made figures such as Banks and Cook, Fletcher Christian and his fellow mutineers on Pitcairn Island into public icons. Bringing together literary texts, works of popular culture, visual art and theatrical performance, Scobie argues that the idea of Oceania functioned variously as reflection, ideal and parody both in very local debates over the problemsof contemporary fame and in wider considerations of national identity, race and empire. RUTH SCOBIE is a Stipendiary Lecturer at Mansfield College, University of Oxford.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCelebritiesxHistoryy18th centuryzGreat Britain. 4aEarly Modern History. 4aEighteenth Century Studies. 4aEnglish & American Literature. 7aHISTORY / Modern / 18th Century.2bisacsh  aBritish identity.  aCaptain James Cook.  aCelebrity Culture.  aJoseph Banks.  aOceania.  acommodified.  aeighteenth century.  aempire.  afame.  aimperial power.  amass print.  anational identity.  apublic icons.  arace.  ascandalous.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2019z978311143102440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781787445062?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781787445062423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781787445062/original  a978-3-11-143102-4  Boydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2019b2019  aGBV-deGruyter-alles